feat(currency): robust baseline priming; simplify init; minimal presets

- Move login-time priming to PLAYER_ENTERING_WORLD and always print summary:
  [AC CT] Login prime summary: checked=X, primed=Y (>0 live), ensured=Z (0 live)
- Add event-time baseline guard in ProcessCurrencyChange():
  - When Total is empty and quantityChange exists, write inferred baseline (new - change)
  - Works regardless of in-memory primed flag
chore(pkg): ignore Docs directory in packaging
chore(release): 3.0.00-alpha

feat(currency): unify source to quantityGainSource; add repair for legacy negative sources

- Use quantityGainSource for both gains and losses; fallback to quantityLostSource only if gain source is missing
- Stop encoding sign in source keys (direction is determined by delta sign)
- Ensure display resolves source labels via SourceCodeTokens with localization
- Add repair commands:
  - /ct repair negative-sources preview — report negative source keys and Total-based baseline reduction
  - /ct repair negative-sources — remove negative keys across all timeframes and subtract Total removals from Total.BaselinePrime.In (clamped)
- Preserve data model and backward compatibility; gold tracker untouched

refactor(currency): prune preset SupportedCurrencies to long‑lived seed; default to 1166

- Reduce preset CurrencyConstants.SupportedCurrencies to a minimal, durable seed:
  - Keep only Timewarped Badge (ID 1166)
- Set 1166 as the default primary currency across modules
  - CurrencyConstants.Defaults.PRIMARY_CURRENCY = 1166
  - CurrencyStorage DEFAULT_CURRENCY = 1166
  - DataManager fallbacks updated:
    - GetSupportedCurrencies() seed uses 1166
    - LoadCurrencySelection() returns 1166 when no selection saved
- Preserve dynamic discovery for all other currencies at runtime

Rationale:
- Remove version-specific presets that don’t age well across expansions
- Keep defaults stable for future updates while maintaining backward compatibility
- Existing per-character selections remain unchanged; defaults apply only when unset

docs(gold-tracker): add event classification reference and data-driven refactor design

- Add Docs/GoldTracker-Event-Classification.md:
  - AC_LOGTYPE definitions table (English/zhCN)
  - Event → AC_LOGTYPE mapping table with notes and code references
  - Special paths (CHAT_MSG_MONEY, PLAYER_MONEY) and fallback behavior

- Add Docs/GoldTracker-Classification-Refactor.md:
  - Data-driven rule schema and dispatcher design
  - Module layout (Core/GoldClassification.lua, Core/GoldClassifier.lua) with no Core.lua edits yet
  - Minimal API, wiring plan, and systematic, safe refactor steps
  - Testing matrix, risks/mitigations, and contributor guidance

No runtime changes; documentation only.
fix(gold): Ensure early, reliable baseline priming after the player fully logs in
fix(currency): first discovery didn’t prime baseline, causing Total vs Live mismatch;

feat(currency): add near-cap warning with configurable thresholds and durations

- Show red alert when post-gain amount >= cap_percent of maxQuantity (live API; fallback totalMax)
- Per-character settings stored under currencyOptions.nearCapAlert:
  - enable (default true)
  - cap_percent (default 0.90)
  - time_visible_sec (default 3.0)
  - fade_duration_sec (default 0.8)
- Slash command: /ct set-paras near-cap-warning [enable=true|false] [cap_percent=0.9] [time_visible_sec=3s] [fade_duration_sec=0.8s]
  - Accepts aliases (time, fade, duration), unit suffixes (s/sec), decimal comma; unknown tokens ignored
- Localized warning string (enUS, zhCN)
- Help text updated for new command

feat(currency): display maxQuantity via live API in /ct show and /ct show-all

- Read caps from C_CurrencyInfo.GetCurrencyInfo using maxQuantity (fallback to totalMax); treat nil/0 as “Unlimited”.
- Add /ct get-currency-info debug command to dump all currency info fields.

fix(prime-mechanism): persist prime state to prevent repeated baseline triggering

- Add persistent 'primed' flag in AccountantClassicDefaultOptions
- Initialize AC_LOG_PRIMED from saved options instead of local variable
- Update all prime setting locations to persist the state
- Ensure prime baseline only triggers once per character lifetime

Fixes issue where prime mechanism triggered on every login instead
of only once when a character first uses the addon
feat(currency-tracker): localize /ct show and /ct show-all outputs; add timeframe label resolver
feat: show currency source in localization name, implemented EN and CN
feat: update currency source tokens to match official Enum.CurrencySource values

refactor(currencyDiscovery): migrate currencyDiscovery to account-wide global store

- Move currencyDiscovery from per-character storage to account-wide Accountant_Classic_CurrencyDB.currencyDiscovery.
- Migrate existing per-character entries once per character (shallow-merge fields, respect existing global values) and mark migrated to avoid repeats.
- Remove legacy per-character discovery table after successful migration.
- Update APIs to always read/write the global store (e.g., GetDiscoveredCurrencies, SaveDiscoveredCurrency); default discovered entries to tracked=true unless explicitly disabled.
- Keep existing data model and period buckets intact; headless design unchanged.

feat(currency-tracker): add `verbose` flag to `/ct show-all` and default-hide untracked currencies

- Add optional `verbose` switch for `/ct show-all` and `/ct show-all-currencies` (e.g., `/ct show-all total verbose`) to include all `currencyData` entries even when `discover list` marks them as `tracked=false`.
- Change default behavior to exclude currencies explicitly marked `tracked=false` in discovery metadata from summaries.
- Seeded currencies without a discovery entry are not filtered by default (`meta == nil` → treated as tracked).
- Update help text in `CurrencyTracker/CurrencyCore.lua:ShowHelp()` to document the `verbose` option.
- Keep headless design and data model intact.

Files:
- [CurrencyTracker/CurrencyCore.lua](cci:7://file:///c:/Users/kamus/CascadeProjects/Accountant_Classic/CurrencyTracker/CurrencyCore.lua:0:0-0:0)

Notes:
- This change affects only display logic. Event logging (baseline prime, meta, writes) still ignores the `tracked` flag unless we add guards later.
feat: add baseline repair commands and enhance currency priming logic

feat(currency-tracker): discovery, localized names, and first-time support fix

- Add dynamic currency discovery with tracked flag and localized name capture
- Record event metadata (gain/lost source counts, last snapshot) for diagnostics
- Fix first-time currency support check so newly discovered IDs record aggregates immediately
- Always display client-localized currency names in all user-facing outputs
- Keep baseline priming: first sighting without explicit quantityChange primes only, not logs
- Update docs with note/TODO to extend metadata to Day/Week/Month/Year and roll over accordingly
chore(toc): normalize Title lines to brand-only across all variants
chore: update addon description to include currency tracking functionality

chore(release): v3.00.00

- Bump TOC versions to v3.00.00 across all variants
- Update Docs/Revision.txt with v3.00.00 notes

refactor(logging): show non-product usage logs only in debug mode

- Gate verbose/non-product logs behind debug checks
- Keep production logs quiet unless debugging is enabled

feat(currency-tracker): initial headless currency tracking with commands, storage, metadata, and repair tools

- Event tracking (modern + legacy)
  - Listen to CURRENCY_DISPLAY_UPDATE (Retail) and BAG_UPDATE (legacy fallback)
  - Compute signed deltas; encode sources as +gainSource / -lostSource

- Persistent storage (per period)
  - Save per-currency, per-period source aggregates: Session, Day, Week, Month, Year, Total
  - Maintain selected currency and tracking options for the character
  - Shift currency logs on login to keep periods current

- Raw event metadata
  - Record both gain and lost raw source codes for each processed change
  - Maintain per-period occurrence counts and a “last” snapshot (including sign/timestamp)

- Slash commands (headless UX)
  - /ct show <timeframe> [currencyid] — detailed view for one currency
  - /ct show-all-currencies <timeframe> — summary across all tracked currencies
  - /ct meta show <timeframe> <id> — inspect raw gain/lost source counts for a currency
  - /ct debug on|off — toggle structured event logging
  - /ct status — show system status

- Repair tools
  - /ct repair remove <id> <amount> <source> (income|outgoing) — cascade true repair across Session/Day/Week/Month/Year/Total
  - /ct repair init — reset currency tracker storage for current character (gold untouched)

- Documentation
  - Extend backend TODOs: per-event log (bounded, with timestamps), zone/activity attribution, retention & cleanup policy, legacy source attribution (best-effort)

wiki_catalogs.name: Project Overview
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on the Accountant_Classic addon. Explain its purpose as a World of Warcraft Classic financial tracking tool that monitors player income and expenses across multiple categories and time periods. Describe the core value proposition: enabling players to analyze gold flow from sources like quests, merchants, repairs, auction house, and more. Cover supported WoW versions (Classic), key features including session/day/week/month/year tracking, cross-character financial overview, minimap button integration via LibDBIcon, and floating money frame display. Discuss the project's architecture at a high level, emphasizing its use of the Ace3 framework for modularity, configuration, and event handling. Include real-world usage scenarios, such as identifying major gold sinks or comparing character wealth. Highlight integration points with LibDataBroker and AceLocale for extensibility and multi-language support. Provide context on how this addon fits into the broader ecosystem of WoW Classic utility addons.

wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the general configuration settings in Accountant_Classic. Explain options such as enabling/disabling the addon, toggling sound alerts on financial events, and setting default time periods for display. Document how these settings are stored using AceDB-3.0 profiles and synchronized across characters when using global settings. Include examples from Config.lua showing how AceConfigRegistry-3.0 registers these options and integrates with the Blizzard Interface Options panel. Address common issues like settings not applying after reload and provide troubleshooting steps. Highlight the relationship between Constants.lua defaults and user-modifiable values in the UI.

Include implementation details such as frame strata management, duration settings, and visual customization options (color, scale, offset). Provide code examples showing event registration and frame creation logic from MoneyFrame.lua. Explain integration points with Core.lua for accessing transaction data and formatting. Address performance considerations like garbage collection of expired frames and throttling mechanisms to prevent UI spam. Describe configuration options exposed to users and how they can be adjusted via the main addon settings. Offer troubleshooting tips for common issues such as missing displays or positioning errors.

Explain how AceDB-3.0 handles per-character and global data storage, and the implications of data deletion on cross-character overviews. Document the confirmation dialogs implemented via LibDialog-1.0 to prevent accidental data loss. Provide examples from Core.lua showing data reset logic and event broadcasting after cleanup operations. Address user concerns about irreversible data removal and suggest backup strategies. Include guidance on managing alts and transferring data between accounts.

wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for advanced features that extend beyond basic financial tracking. Cover the LibDataBroker integration that enables data sharing with other addons and display through various LDB consumers. Explain the technical implementation of the zone-level breakdown system and how location context is maintained during transactions. Include performance considerations for the floating frame feature and how it avoids UI clutter. wiki_catalogs.name: Technical Architecture
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create architectural documentation for the Accountant_Classic codebase. Describe the component-based design using the Ace3 framework, where Core.lua acts as the primary addon controller managing event registration, data initialization, and inter-module coordination. Explain the MVC-like pattern with Constants.lua providing data model definitions, Core.lua handling business logic, and XML templates defining UI structure. Document the event-driven architecture that responds to WoW client events like PLAYER_MONEY, MAIL_INBOX_UPDATE, and AUCTION_HOUSE_SHOW. Detail the separation of concerns between modules, particularly how MoneyFrame.lua operates as an independent but integrated component. Include infrastructure requirements such as the dependency on LibStub for library loading and CallbackHandler-1.0 for event management. Address scalability considerations for handling large datasets across multiple characters and the efficiency of AceDB's storage mechanism.

wiki_catalogs.name: API Reference
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create API documentation for the public interfaces exposed by Accountant_Classic. Document all public methods in the addon object accessible to other addons, including configuration accessors, data retrieval functions, and event registration points. For Core.lua, detail the main addon methods like OnInitialize, OnEnable, and event handler signatures. For Config.lua, document the options table structure used by AceConfigRegistry-3.0 and how external addons can programmatically access configuration values. Include examples of how other addons might interact with Accountant_Classic through LibDataBroker feeds or direct API calls. Specify parameters, return values, and error conditions for each public function. Address versioning considerations and backward compatibility for addon developers. Document event hooks that third-party addons can listen for, such as when financial data is updated or when the UI is shown.

Document Constants.logmodes for time period definitions and Constants.logtypes for transaction source categories. Include field definitions, data types, and relationships between entities. wiki_overview.content:
<blog>
# Accountant_Classic Project Analysis

## 1. Project Introduction

Accountant_Classic is a World of Warcraft addon designed to track players' monetary transactions within the game. The addon serves as a financial management tool that monitors incoming and outgoing gold across various activities such as quests, merchant transactions, repairs, and other in-game economic interactions.

The core purpose of this project is to provide players with detailed insights into their character's financial activities by categorizing and logging money changes across different time periods (session, day, week, month, etc.). This helps players understand their spending patterns and income sources in the game.

The target audience includes WoW players who want to track their in-game economy across multiple characters and servers, particularly those interested in optimizing their gold management strategies. The addon appears to be specifically tailored for the WoW Classic experience, with support for various Classic versions including Era, TBC, and WotLK.

## 2. Technical Architecture

The project follows a modular architecture built on the Ace3 framework ecosystem, which is a collection of Lua libraries commonly used in World of Warcraft addon development. The architecture consists of a core addon with several specialized components that handle different aspects of functionality.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Accountant_Classic] --> B[AceAddon-3.0]
    A --> C[AceDB-3.0]
    A --> D[AceConfig-3.0]
    A --> E[AceEvent-3.0]
    A --> F[AceGUI-3.0]
    A --> G[AceHook-3.0]
    A --> H[AceLocale-3.0]
    A --> I[LibDataBroker-1.1]
    A --> J[LibDBIcon-1.0]
    A --> K[LibUIDropDownMenu]
    A --> L[LibDialog-1.0]
    B --> M[Core Functionality]
    C --> N[Data Storage]
    D --> O[Configuration UI]
    F --> P[UI Components]
    I --> Q[LDB Integration]
    J --> R[Minimap Button]
```

The system follows a component-based design where the main addon registers modules and services that handle specific responsibilities. The data flow begins with WoW's event system, which triggers when money-related events occur (PLAYER_MONEY, CHAT_MSG_MONEY, etc.). These events are captured by the addon's event handlers, processed to determine the transaction type and amount, and then stored in the database.

The UI layer consists of a main frame with multiple tabs that display financial data in different time contexts, along with dropdown menus for character selection and configuration options. The UI is defined using XML templates that describe the visual layout, while Lua scripts handle the logic and data binding.

## 3. Key Implementation

### Main Entry Points
- [Core.lua](Core/Core.lua)
- [Core.xml](Core/Core.xml)

### Core Modules
- [Config.lua](Core/Config.lua) - Configuration management and options interface
- [Constants.lua](Core/Constants.lua) - Application constants and configuration
- [MoneyFrame.lua](Core/MoneyFrame.lua) - Floating money display module

### Configuration Approach
- [Constants.lua](Core/Constants.lua) - Defines default settings and configuration values
- [Config.lua](Core/Config.lua) - Implements the options interface using AceConfig

### External Dependencies
- [Libs/](Libs/) - Contains all external libraries including Ace3 framework components and other dependencies

### Integration Points
- [Core.lua](Core/Core.lua) - Main integration point for WoW events and API calls
- [Bindings.xml](Bindings.xml) - Key binding integration with WoW interface

```mermaid
graph LR
    A[WoW Event System] --> B[Core.lua]
    B --> C[Constants.lua]
    B --> D[Config.lua]
    B --> E[MoneyFrame.lua]
    C --> F[Data Structure]
    D --> G[UI Configuration]
    E --> H[Floating Display]
    B --> I[Database Storage]
    I --> J[Accountant_ClassicSaveData]
    B --> K[LibDataBroker]
    B --> L[LibDBIcon]
```

## 4. Key Features

The addon provides comprehensive financial tracking across multiple dimensions:

```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> Initialization
    Initialization --> DataCollection: OnLoad
    DataCollection --> SessionTracking: PLAYER_MONEY
    DataCollection --> DailyTracking: Zone Change
    DataCollection --> WeeklyTracking: Week Start
    DataCollection --> MonthlyTracking: Month Start
    DataCollection --> TransactionLogging: Various Events
    TransactionLogging --> Categorization
    Categorization --> Storage
    Storage --> Display
    Display --> MainFrame
    Display --> MinimapButton
    Display --> FloatingFrame
    MainFrame --> TabbedInterface
    TabbedInterface --> SessionTab
    TabbedInterface --> DailyTab
    TabbedInterface --> WeeklyTab
    TabbedInterface --> MonthlyTab
    TabbedInterface --> AllCharactersTab
    FloatingFrame --> RealTimeTracking
```

The implementation highlights include:

- **Multi-version Support**: The addon detects the WoW version and adjusts its behavior accordingly, supporting both Classic and Retail versions with different feature sets.
- **Comprehensive Event Tracking**: Monitors a wide range of money-related events including training costs, taxi fares, trade transactions, auction house activities, repairs, mail, quests, and looting.
- **Cross-Character Management**: Allows players to view and manage financial data across multiple characters and servers.
- **Flexible Display Options**: Provides both a detailed main interface and compact display options through minimap buttons and floating frames.
- **Data Persistence**: Uses AceDB for reliable data storage that persists between game sessions.

The project demonstrates a well-structured approach to WoW addon development, leveraging established libraries and design patterns within the WoW addon ecosystem.
</blog>
